title: Railroad - Transclusion and Macros

! Transclusion and Macros — Railroad Diagrams

This tiddler presents the same grammar as [[EBNF - Transclusion and Macros]], but using railroad diagrams for visual clarity. Follow the tracks left-to-right to see valid syntax paths.

!! Transclusion

Transclusion embeds the content of one tiddler inside another. Both block and inline forms exist (see [[Block vs Inline|Railroad - Transclusion and Macros##Block vs Inline]] below). Five patterns are supported, all sharing a common structure.

!!! ~TiddlerRef

A tiddler reference names a tiddler with an optional field (`!!`) or index (`##`) accessor.

<$railroad text=""" <"title"> [("!!" <"field"> | "##" <"index">)] """/>

!!! Full Transclusion

Double braces wrap a transclusion spec: an optional tiddler reference, an optional template (after `||`), and zero or more positional parameters (each after `|`).

<$railroad text=""" "{{" [<"TiddlerRef">] ["||" <"template">] [{:"|" <"param">}] "}}" """/>

''Examples:''

* `{{MyTiddler}}` — basic transclusion
* `{{MyTiddler!!caption}}` — field transclusion
* `{{MyTiddler##key}}` — index transclusion
* `{{MyTiddler||$:/templates/MyTemplate}}` — template transclusion
* `{{MyTiddler||MyTemplate|one|two}}` — parameterised transclusion

!! Filtered Transclusion

Filtered transclusion uses triple braces and produces a `<$list>` widget at runtime. An optional tooltip (after `|`) and/or template (after `||`) may be specified inside the braces. Style declarations and CSS classes can follow outside.

<$railroad text=""" "{{{" <"filter-expr"> ["|" <"tooltip">] ["||" <"template">] "}}}" [<"style-defs">] ["." <"class-names">] """/>

The style portion sits between the closing `}}}` and is terminated by `}`. Class names are dot-separated after the final `}`.

''Examples:''

* `{{{[tag[draft]]}}}` — basic filtered transclusion
* `{{{[tag[draft]]|Draft items}}}` — with tooltip
* `{{{[tag[draft]]||$:/templates/item}}}` — with template
* `{{{[tag[draft]]|Drafts||$:/templates/item}}}` — tooltip and template
* `{{{[tag[draft]]}}}width:100%;.myclass` — with style and classes

!! Macro Call

Macro calls are delimited by `<<` and `>>`. A macro name is followed by zero or more space-separated parameters.

!!! ~MacroParam

Each parameter has an optional name (followed by `:`) and a value. Five quoting styles are available for values.

<$railroad text=`[<"name"> ":"] ('"""' <"any content"> '"""' | '"' <"no-dquote"> '"' | "'" <"no-squote"> "'" | "[[" <"bracket-content"> "]]" | <"unquoted">) `/>

The first alternative is triple-double-quote (`"""`) — it accepts any content including newlines.

!!! Full Macro Call

<$railroad text=""" "<<" <"macro-name"> [{<"MacroParam">}] ">>" """/>

''Examples:''

* `<<now "DDth MMM YYYY">>` — positional parameter
* `<<tabs tabsList:"[tag[docs]]" default:"Intro">>` — named parameters
* `<<myMacro [[value with spaces]]>>` — bracket-quoted value

!! MVV Display (inline only)

The multi-valued variable display syntax provides a concise way to show variable values or filter results inline. Unlike the other constructs here, MVV display has ''no block form''.

!!! Variable Display

Double parentheses display a variable's value. An optional separator (after `||`) joins multiple values. The default separator is `", "`.

<$railroad text=""" "((" <"var-name"> ["||" <"separator">] "))" """/>

!!! Filter Display

Triple parentheses display filter results. An optional separator (after `||`) joins the results.

<$railroad text=""" "(((" <"filter-expr"> ["||" <"separator">] ")))" """/>

''Examples:''

* `((myVar))` — display variable value
* `((myList||, ))` — display with comma separator
* `(((  [tag[task]get[title]]  )))` — display filter results
* `(((  [tag[task]get[title]]  ||; )))` — filter results with semicolon separator

!! Block vs Inline

Transclusion (`{{...}}`), filtered transclusion (`{{{...}}}`), and macro calls (`<<...>>`) each have ''both'' block and inline parser rules:

* ''Block form'' — the construct must appear alone on its line, followed by a newline or end of input. The parse node gets `isBlock: true`, producing `<div>` wrappers.
* ''Inline form'' — the construct appears within a run of text. Output is rendered inline within `<span>` or `<p>` elements.

MVV display `((...))` and `(((...)))` is the exception: it exists ''only as an inline rule''.